  Analysis: Arg Registers for the Stackless Execution IR

  1. What Problem Arg Registers Solve

  In the current design, the stackless-exec-ir uses uniform named registers (r0, r1, ...). During the second translation
  to micro-ops, every call requires:
  - Args: Copy each argument from the caller's register slots to the callee's sequential arg slots
  - Returns: Copy each return value from the callee's sequential return slots back to caller registers

  With arg registers (a0, a1, ...), the caller frame layout places arg registers at the end, overlapping the callee's arg
   slots. If a value is produced directly into a0, the second translation can skip the copy entirely — the value is
  already in the right physical location.

  2. Pros

  Performance wins:
  - Eliminates arg/return copies in the second translation. This is the primary benefit. Every avoided copy saves a
  sized-slot memcpy in the micro-op interpreter. For functions with many calls (the common case in Move), this compounds.
  - Reduces instruction count in micro-ops. Each eliminated copy is one fewer micro-op to dispatch.
  - Better cache locality. Values destined for a call end up in contiguous memory (the arg area) without an intermediate
  hop through scattered register slots.
  - Chained call optimization. For f(g(x)), the return value of g (in a0) is already the argument to f — zero copies
  through the entire chain.

  Design wins:
  - Explicit dataflow to the calling convention. The IR makes the caller-callee interface visible, which helps the second
   translation emit tighter code without needing its own analysis pass.
  - Naturally extends the existing hint/coalescing patterns. V1's destination hints and V2's StLoc look-ahead already try
   to place values where they'll be consumed; arg registers are the logical next step for call targets.

  3. Cons

  Complexity costs:
  - Dual register namespace. Every part of the pipeline — IR representation, display, get_defs_uses, rename_instr,
  renumber_registers, copy propagation, DCE — must understand that a_j registers are fundamentally different from r_k
  registers.
  - Type variability. Unlike r-registers (one type per register for the function lifetime), a-registers change type at
  every call site. reg_types: Vec<Type> no longer suffices; you need per-call-site type info or accept that arg registers
   are "untyped" in the IR's type vector.
  - Optimization passes must be careful. Copy propagation cannot propagate across a call boundary through an arg
  register. DCE must recognize that a def into a_j is live if a subsequent call uses a_j. Register renumbering must
  preserve the arg register namespace.
  - Frame size increase. Every function gains max_arg_regs extra slots in its frame, even for call sites where the
  optimization doesn't fire. (Usually minor, since these overlap with callee frames anyway.)

  Semantic subtleties:
  - Arg registers are "volatile" across calls. A value in a0 is destroyed by any call. This is a fundamentally different
  liveness property from r-registers and requires careful tracking.
  - Inter-call interference. If a function has two calls in the same block, the arg registers from the first call are
  clobbered by setup for the second. Values that must survive between calls cannot use arg registers.
  - Closure calls complicate the layout. CallClosure includes the closure object as an extra argument, which needs to
  participate in the arg register scheme or be excluded.

  4. Safety Conditions for Arg Register Assignment

  4a. For argument a_j at a call site C at instruction index ci:

  A value currently in register r (defined at instruction di) can be assigned to a_j if all of the following hold:

  1. Temp only: r >= num_pinned (not a parameter or declared local). Parameters/locals have persistent storage, may be
  borrowed, and may be needed on other control flow paths.
  2. Same basic block: di and ci are in the same basic block. Across block boundaries, the value may be live on another
  path and we cannot safely move its storage to a volatile location.
  3. No intervening call: There is no Call/CallGeneric/CallClosure instruction in the range (di, ci). Any call clobbers
  all arg registers.
  4. Dead after the call: r has no uses after ci. Since the call consumes arg registers and potentially overwrites them
  with return values, r's value would be lost. (In Move, function args are consumed, so the bytecode verifier already
  guarantees moved values aren't reused. The condition matters for CopyLoc-originated temps that might be used again.)
  5. No conflicting write to a_j: No other instruction in (di, ci) writes to a_j. In practice this means if we've already
   decided to place another arg a_k (k != j) for the same call, the def of a_k doesn't clobber a_j. Since a_j and a_k are
   distinct registers, this condition is trivially satisfied — the concern is only about a_j specifically being written
  twice.
  6. Reads of r between di and ci are safe: If r is read between its definition and the call (e.g., r is used as an
  operand of some other instruction AND as arg j), the renaming r → a_j means those reads become reads of a_j. This is
  safe as long as conditions 3 and 5 hold (the value in a_j isn't clobbered).

  Important note on ordering: Args do not need to be produced in a0, a1, a2 order. Since a0 and a1 are distinct
  registers, defining a1 before a0 is fine. The only constraint is "no clobber of the same arg register," which can't
  happen when each arg position is distinct.

  4b. For return value a_k at a call site C at instruction index ci:

  A return value currently assigned to register r can remain in a_k if:

  1. Temp only: r >= num_pinned.
  2. All uses before next call: Every use of r occurs before the next Call/CallGeneric/CallClosure in the same basic
  block (or before the block ends, if there is no subsequent call). The next call clobbers all arg registers.
  3. No conflicting arg register setup: Between ci and the next call, if we're also setting up arg registers for the next
   call, none of those setups write to a_k before r's last use. In practice, this means r's last use is before any
  instruction that defines a_k for the next call.

  Special chained case: If r (return value a_k from call C1) is used as argument a_k of the very next call C2, no copy is
   needed at all — the value stays in a_k. This handles f(g(x)) perfectly.

  5. Pass Design for V2

  V2 is the more natural fit because it has explicit SSA within blocks and liveness information. The arg register pass
  would run as a post-optimization pass, after fusion/copy-prop/DCE but before register renumbering.

  Algorithm (linear-time per basic block):

  for each basic block B:
    // Precompute: for each temp register r, find its def position and last-use position
    // (single forward scan)
    def_pos[r] = instruction index where r is defined
    last_use[r] = instruction index where r is last used

    // Collect call sites in order
    calls = [(ci, args, rets) for each Call/CallGeneric/CallClosure in B]

    // Track which instruction indices are calls (for "no intervening call" check)
    call_set = {ci for (ci, _, _) in calls}

    // === Argument assignment ===
    for each (ci, args, rets) in calls:
      for j in 0..args.len():
        r = args[j]
        if r < num_pinned: continue

        di = def_pos[r]
        // Condition 2: same block (guaranteed since we're iterating within B)
        // Condition 3: no call in (di, ci)
        if any c in call_set where di < c < ci: continue
        // Condition 4: dead after call
        if last_use[r] > ci: continue

        // All conditions met: mark args[j] for arg register a_j
        rename r → ARG(j) in range [di, ci]

    // === Return value assignment ===
    for each (ci, args, rets) in calls:
      next_call = first call index > ci in call_set (or end of block)
      for k in 0..rets.len():
        r = rets[k]
        if r < num_pinned: continue

        // Condition: all uses of r before next_call
        if last_use[r] >= next_call: continue

        // Mark rets[k] for arg register a_k
        rename r → ARG(k) in range [ci, last_use[r]]

    // Compute max_arg_regs for this function
    max_arg_regs = max(max_arg_regs, max(args.len(), rets.len())) for each call

  The renaming step replaces all occurrences of r (both defs and uses) in the identified range with the arg register
  index. This can be done in a single forward scan using a HashMap<Reg, ArgReg> that's populated and cleared per call
  site.

  Complexity: O(n) per block where n is the number of instructions — each instruction is visited a constant number of
  times.

  6. Pass Design for V1

  V1 can integrate arg registers via its existing destination hint mechanism. Currently, compute_hints looks ahead for
  StLoc patterns. This would be extended:

  1. During hint computation: When the forward scan identifies that a produced value feeds directly into a Call as
  argument j (via the simulated stack), emit a hint to place the value in a_j rather than an r-register.
  2. During convert_bytecode for Call: After popping args from the simulated stack, check which args are already in arg
  registers (due to hints). For those, no Copy/Move is needed. Allocate return values to a_k registers directly.
  3. Safety is simpler in V1: The stack simulation naturally tracks value flow. If a value was pushed, never read by
  anything else, and popped for a call, it's guaranteed to be single-use and dead after the call. The hint system already
   handles the "don't allocate to a register that's on the stack" invariant.

  The key change: alloc_or_hint would gain arg register hints alongside StLoc hints, and the hint priority would be: arg
  register hint > StLoc hint > type-recycled allocation.

  7. IR Representation Changes

  The cleanest approach is to partition the Reg space:

  pub struct FunctionIR {
      pub num_params: Reg,
      pub num_locals: Reg,
      pub num_regs: Reg,        // r-registers: 0..num_regs-1
      pub num_arg_regs: Reg,    // arg registers: num_regs..num_regs+num_arg_regs-1
      pub instrs: Vec<Instr>,
      pub reg_types: Vec<Type>, // only for 0..num_regs-1 (r-registers)
  }

  With helper predicates:

  fn is_arg_reg(&self, r: Reg) -> bool { r >= self.num_regs && r < self.num_regs + self.num_arg_regs }
  fn arg_index(&self, r: Reg) -> u16 { r - self.num_regs }  // a0, a1, ...

  Display would render r >= num_regs as a0, a1, etc. The existing rename_instr / get_defs_uses infrastructure works
  unchanged since it operates on Reg = u16 values. The renumber_registers pass would need to preserve arg registers
  (don't compress them into the r-register range).

  Arg registers intentionally have no entry in reg_types — their types vary per call site and are recovered from the call
   instruction's signature during the second translation.

  8. Impact on Existing Optimization Passes

  - Fusion (field access, immediate binops): No change needed. These fuse consecutive instructions and don't interact
  with call sites.
  - Copy propagation: Must not propagate a def of a_j past a call instruction (the call clobbers it). Add a check: if
  is_arg_reg(r), kill the mapping at the next call.
  - Dead instruction elimination: Must recognize that a def to a_j followed by a call that uses a_j is live. The existing
   backward liveness scan already handles this correctly if get_defs_uses for Call returns arg registers as uses — which
  it does, since they appear in the args Vec.
  - Register renumbering: Must treat arg registers as a separate namespace. Only renumber r-registers (0..num_regs-1);
  leave arg registers (num_regs..num_regs+num_arg_regs-1) in place.

  9. Summary of Recommendation

  The arg register design is sound and addresses a real inefficiency in the micro-op calling convention. The conditions
  are well-defined and can be checked in linear time. For the pipeline you keep:

  - If V2: Implement as a post-optimization pass using the liveness data already computed during allocation. It
  integrates naturally with the SSA + greedy allocation model.
  - If V1: Extend the destination hint system to include call-arg hints alongside StLoc hints. This is more tightly
  coupled to the conversion but avoids a separate pass.

  The main risk is complexity in maintaining two register namespaces across all passes. Keeping the FunctionIR
  representation simple (arg regs as high Reg values with a num_arg_regs field, no reg_types entries) minimizes the blast
   radius.

  After SSA conversion, before physical allocation:

  1. Compute use lists for SSA values.
  2. Mark candidate values with preferred class Arg(i).
  3. Mark ordinary values with class Frame.
  4. Run allocation with Arg(i) precolored.
  5. Allow use-then-def reuse at calls:
      - argument a{i} dies at call entry
      - return a{i} is defined by the call


  When An Argument Can Become a{i}

  A value v can be placed directly in a{i} for a call arg or final ret slot i if all are true:

  1. The sink position is fixed: call arg i or return slot i.
  2. v’s type matches that slot’s type.
  3. v has a single clear reaching def.
  4. v is not needed after that sink.
  5. No intervening call/branch/label/clobber would invalidate a{i}.
  6. No other promoted value needs a{i} over the same live range.
  7. The defining instruction can legally target an arbitrary destination.
  8. v is not required to remain in a frame register for specs/debug instrumentation.

  When A Return Value Can Stay In a{i}

  Call result i can remain in a{i} if all are true:

  1. It is produced by the call in slot i.
  2. All uses happen before the next clobber of a{i}.
  3. It is not live across a block boundary.
  4. Its consumers can read a{i} directly.
  5. It is not forced into a frame register by specs/debugging.

